ManSection.Description:
S and T
are numerical semigroups. Computes the intersection of S and T
(which is a numerical semigroup).

gap> S := NumericalSemigroup("modular", 5,53);
<Modular numerical semigroup satisfying 5x mod 53 <= x >
gap> T := NumericalSemigroup(2,17);
<Modular numerical semigroup satisfying 17x mod 34 <= x >
gap> SmallElementsOfNumericalSemigroup(S);
[ 0, 11, 12, 13, 22, 23, 24, 25, 26, 32, 33, 34, 35, 36, 37, 38, 39, 43 ]
gap> SmallElementsOfNumericalSemigroup(T);
[ 0, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 16 ]
gap> IntersectionOfNumericalSemigroups(S,T);
<Numerical semigroup>
gap> SmallElementsOfNumericalSemigroup(last);
[ 0, 12, 22, 23, 24, 25, 26, 32, 33, 34, 35, 36, 37, 38, 39, 43 ]

S is a numerical semigroup and n is an integer.
Computes the quotient of S by n, that is, the set \{ x\in {\mathbb N}\ |\  nx \in S\}, which is again a numerical semigroup.
S / n may be used as a short for QuotientOfNumericalSemigroup(S, n).

gap> s:=NumericalSemigroup(3,29);
<Modular numerical semigroup satisfying 58x mod 87 <= x >
gap> SmallElementsOfNumericalSemigroup(s);
[ 0, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 21, 24, 27, 29, 30, 32, 33, 35, 36, 38,
39, 41, 42, 44, 45, 47, 48, 50, 51, 53, 54, 56 ]
gap> t:=QuotientOfNumericalSemigroup(s,7);
<Numerical semigroup>
gap> SmallElementsOfNumericalSemigroup(t);
[ 0, 3, 5, 6, 8 ]
gap> u := s / 7;
<Numerical semigroup>
gap> SmallElementsOfNumericalSemigroup(u);
[ 0, 3, 5, 6, 8 ]

S is a numerical semigroup, and a and b are positive integers.
Computes  a S\cup \{b,b+1,\to\}. If b is smaller than a c, with c the conductor of S, then a warning is displayed.

gap> N:=NumericalSemigroup(1);;
gap> s:=MultipleOfNumericalSemigroup(N,4,20);;
gap> SmallElements(s);
[ 0, 4, 8, 12, 16, 20 ]

S is a numerical semigroup, and E and ideal of S with E\subseteq S, and b are positive odd integer in S.
Computes  2S\cup (2E+b).

  gap> s:=NumericalSemigroup(3,5,7);
  <Numerical semigroup with 3 generators>
  gap> e:=6+s;
  <Ideal of numerical semigroup>
  gap> ndup:=NumericalDuplication(s,e,3);
  <Numerical semigroup>
  gap> SmallElements(ndup);
  [ 0, 6, 10, 12, 14, 15, 16, 18, 20, 21, 22, 24 ]

S is a numerical semigroup, and a and b are lists of positive integers, such that b[i+1]\ge a[i]b[i].
Computes inductively S_0=\mathbb N and S_{i+1}=a[i]S_i\cup \{a[i]b[i],a[i]b[i]+1,\to\}, and returns S_{k}, with k the length of a and b.

gap> s:=InductiveNumericalSemigroup([4,2],[5,23]);;
gap> SmallElements(s);
[ 0, 8, 16, 24, 32, 40, 42, 44, 46 ]
